05845nam a22008175i 9781800109025DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97818001090257 a10.1515/97818001090252doi  a(DE-B1597)676342  a(OCoLC)1354207328  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a944/.014092qOCoLC223/eng/2022121600aCharlemagne in Italy /ced. by Jane E. Everson.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2023] 1bD.S.Brewer, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b5 b/w, 3 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBristol Studies in Medieval Cultures ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Contributors -- tGeneral Preface: Charlemagne: A European Icon -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbreviations -- tA Note on Terminology -- tIntroduction -- t1. The First Franco-Italian Vernacular Textual Witnesses of the Charlemagne Epic Tradition in the Italian Peninsula: Hybrid Forms -- t2. The Italian cantari on Charlemagne -- t3 Carlo Magno, Ideal Progenitor of Country and Lineage: the Image of Charlemagne in the Prose Compilations of Andrea da Barberino -- t5 Matteo Maria Boiardo: Inamoramento de Orlando -- t6. Crisis and Continuity at the Turn of the Century -- t7. From Emperor to Pawn: Charlemagne in the Orlando Furioso -- t8. An Undying Tradition: the Afterlife of Charlemagne in Italy -- tAfterword: Charlemagne in Italy: a Never-Ending Story -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn exploration of the many depictions of Charlemagne in the Italian tradition of chivalric narratives in verse and prose.Chivalric tales and narratives concerning Charlemagne were composed and circulated in Italy from the early fourteenth to the mid-sixteenth century (and indeed subsequently flourished in forms of popular theatre which continue today). But are they history or fiction? Myth or fact? Cultural memory or deliberate appropriation? Elite culture or popular entertainment? Oral or written, performed or read? Beginning in the age of Dante with the earliest tales composed for Italians in the hybrid language of Franco-Italian, which draw inspiration from the French tradition of Charlemagne narratives, the volume considers the compositions of anonymous reciters of cantari and the prose versions of the Florentine Andrea da Barberino, before discussing the major literary contributions to the genre by Luigi Pulci, Matteo Maria Boiardo and Ludovico Ariosto. The focus throughout is on the ways in which the portrait of Charlemagne, seen as both Emperor and King of France, is persistently ambiguous, affected by the contemporary political situation and historical events such as invasion and warfare. He emerges through these texts in myriad guises, from positive and admirable to negative and despised.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aItalian literaturexHistory and criticismy15th century. 0aItalian literaturexHistory and criticismyTo 1400. 0aItalien. 0aLiteratur. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCharlemagne.  aDante.  aFranco-Italian.  aItaly.  achivalric narratives.  achivalric tales.  afifteenth century.  afourteenth century.  amedieval literature.  amedieval studies.  asixteenth century.1 aAiles, Marianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennet, Philip E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoscolo, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDegl'Innocenti, Luca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDegl’Innocenti, Luca, econtributor.4ctb